<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en" data-bs-theme="light">

<head>
    <title>Assembler Project - Liad Firouz</title>
    <%- include('partials/head') %>
    <style>
        .project-hero { background-color: #f8f9fa; padding: 4rem 0; }
        .tech-box { background-color: #f1f3f5; border-left: 5px solid #0d6efd; padding: 1.5rem; margin: 2rem 0; }
        .code-highlight { font-family: monospace; color: #d63384; }
    </style>
</head>

<body>
    <%- include('partials/header') %>

    <main class="container py-5">
        <div class="project-hero text-center mb-5 rounded">
            <h1 class="display-3 fw-bold">Custom Two-Pass Assembler</h1>
            <p class="lead text-muted">Systems Programming & Low-Level Architecture in C</p>
            <a href="https://github.com/LiadFirouz/Assembler" target="_blank" class="btn btn-dark btn-lg mt-3">View Source Code</a>
        </div>

        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-lg-8">
                <h3>The Challenge: Mastering Pointers and Symbolic Logic</h3>
                <p>
                    Throughout this project, the most significant challenge was memory management at the C level. Navigating between functions while ensuring pointer integrity required rigorous attention to data lifecycles—any minor mistake in pointer management frequently led to memory leaks or frustrating segmentation faults.
                </p>
                <p>
                    The complexity peaked during the implementation of the Symbol Table. As the assembler operates using a 'Two-Pass' methodology, I had to construct a dynamic table to efficiently manage addresses and symbols, while simultaneously resolving forward references.
                </p>
                
                

                <div class="tech-box">
                    <h5 class="fw-bold">Key Takeaways from the Development Process:</h5>
                    <ul class="mb-0">
                        <li><strong>Memory Management:</strong> Mastering manual <span class="code-highlight">malloc</span> and <span class="code-highlight">free</span> cycles.</li>
                        <li><strong>Data Structures:</strong> Implementing linked lists for efficient symbol storage.</li>
                        <li><strong>Workflow:</strong> Utilizing Gemini as a pair-programming partner to simulate edge-case logic and optimize debugging.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h3>Debugging with AI</h3>
                <p>
                    During development, I leveraged Gemini to simulate logical bugs and optimize search algorithms within the symbol table. Using AI did not replace the hard work; instead, it served as a "debugging partner" that helped identify memory management anomalies early on, ultimately allowing me to focus on the system's overall architecture rather than just squashing bugs.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="text-center mt-5">
            <a href="/" class="btn btn-outline-dark">← Back to Portfolio</a>
        </div>
    </main>

    <div class="container">
        <%- include('partials/footer') %>
    </div>
</body>
</html>